text:
 Make it work for you. You will always have some type of DOF in your shots so make it work for you, not against you. Use the modes that your camera came with. That is the quickest and easiest way to get the right depth of field. Learn what controls your depth of field and how. Aperture{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Shoot-for-Depth-of-Field-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Shoot-for-Depth-of-Field-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/16/Shoot-for-Depth-of-Field-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Shoot-for-Depth-of-Field-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/2.5/">Creative Commons</a><br>
